	<h1>Lifetime Learning Tax Credit</h1>
	
	<p>Keep in mind that a tax credit is not financial aid.  No check gets cut from anyone to the student, parents, or school.  A tax credit is a direct reduction of the amount of tax money you owe the IRS.  A tax credit is different than a tax deduction.  With deductions, the amount of income the IRS may tax is reduced.</p>
	
	<h3>Who Qualifies for this Tax Credit?</h3>
	
	<p>Because a tax credit is a direct reduction of the amount you owe the IRS, one needs to owe taxes to qualify for a tax credit such as the Lifetime Learning Tax Credit.  If you owe no taxes, then you have no eligibility for this tax credit.  If you owe less in taxes than the total amount of the credit, the credit will reduce your liability to the IRS to zero dollars.</p>
	<p>This benefit is available to parents and any or all dependents. There is no requirement for the student to be at least 1/2-time or be in a degree seeking program as with the Lifetime Learning Tax Credit.  Nor does the drug conviction rule apply.</p>
	






<p><strong>Maximum credit </strong></p>
<p>Up to $2,000 credit per return</p>

<p><strong>Limit on modified adjusted gross income (MAGI)</strong></p>
<p>$124,000 if married filing jointly; $62,000 if single, head of household, or qualifying widow(er)</p>

<p><strong>Credit Limit</strong></p>
<p>To the amount of tax you must pay on your taxable income</p>

<p><strong>Period of Eligibility </strong></p>
<p>Available for all years of postsecondary education and for courses to acquire or improve job skills</p>

<p><strong>Term of Eligibility</strong></p>
<p>Available for an unlimited number of years</p>

<p><strong>Term of when the payments were made </strong></p>
<p>The tax year in question and 3 months into the next tax year.</p>

<p><strong>Type of program required </strong></p>
<p>Student does not need to be pursuing a program leading to a degree or other recognized education credential</p>

<p><strong>Required Enrollment </strong></p>
<p>Available for one or more courses</p>

<p><strong>Qualified expenses </strong></p>
<p>Tuition and fees required for enrollment or attendance (including amounts required to be paid to the institution for course-related books, supplies, and equipment)</p>

<p><strong>Felony drug conviction </strong></p>
<p>Felony drug convictions do not make the student ineligible</p>












